Part I - (LOAN DATASET PRESENTATION)¶

Introduction¶

The general objective of this project is to present visualizations to show the relationship between features as provided in the Prosper loan dataset such as BorrowerRate, loan Term, BorrowerAPR,loan Status, ProsperRating(Alpha, occupation and many more.

Dataset Overview¶

The Loan dataset provided by Prosper is used for the presentation, it contains both quantitative and qualitative features. This data set contains 113,937 rows of loans with 81 columns for variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate, current loan status, borrower income, Prosper score, loan term and many more.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The data contains 113066 loans as rows and 81 features as columns. The features are about loan information and borrower information.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features under consideration are loanStatus, Occupation, Term and EmploymentStatus of applicants. As a potential bororwer Im also interested in the interest rate and APR of the loan. The APR is the interest rate plus some fees, so it is mostly higher than the interest rate. Interestingly, the LoanStatus information can be useful for a predictive model for risk management in Prosper.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Other features such as Term, MonthlyLoanPayment, ProsperRating (numeric), LoanOriginationDate, ProsperRating (Alpha), CreditGrade, ProsperScore, DebtToIncomeRatio, IncomeRange will support in the investigation of the variables of interest.

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, I investigate distributions of individual variables. I elaborate on unusual points or outliers, take a deeper look to clean things up and look at relationships between variables.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

ProsperRating and ProsperScore have a significant impact on BorrowerRate. BorrowerRate are negatively correlated with ProsperRating. There is also a strong postive relationship between BorrowerAPR and BorrowerRate. The BorrowerAPR is the annual cost of a loan to a borrower. Unlike an interest rate, it includes other charges or fees (such as mortgage insurance, most closing costs, discount points and loan origination fees) to reflect the total cost of the loan.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Only a few borrowers have defaulted loans with Prosper Rating of AA. The proportion of defaulted loans in the lower rating groups are significant higher, considering that in HR group the defaulted loan is more than half of the completed loans.

Observing the Borrower rates over time, there is no notable monotonic behaviors. Hence, Time effect may not be a better independent feature to predict a borrowers interest rate.

Conclusions¶

The Prosper Rating and Prosper score feature has proven to be efficient to predict whether there will be a defaulted loan or not. So Prosper would be able to use this score to set the borrowes interest rate. This is evident as the strongest relationships were found for the Prosper Rating versus Loan Status and the Prosper Score vs. Borrowers rate, overtime. However, the Borrower rate over time shows no monotonic behaviors.Term may not be a better independent feature to predict a borrowers interest rate.
